				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">The Endangered Pro-Choice Republican</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Phoebe Lett			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-12-24T15:00:57+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">December 24, 2015 10:00 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">December 24, 2015 10:00 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/12/24/the-endangered-pro-choice-republican/" data-title="The Endangered Pro-Choice Republican" data-description="A majority of Americans support abortion under some circumstances, but most Republicans arenât listening to them.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/12/24/opinion/24lettWEB/24lettWEB-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/12/24/opinion/24lettWEB/24lettWEB-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/12/24/opinion/24lettWEB/24lettWEB-blog480.jpg" id="100000004110796" width="480" height="319" alt="Senator Lindsey Graham."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="319"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Senator Lindsey Graham.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Steve Pope/Getty Images </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Long before his Monday announcement <a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/12/21/lindsey-graham-ends-his-presidential-campaign/">ending his presidential campaign</a>, Senator Lindsey Graham of South Carolina seemed to transform from a candidate seeking to unify the party into an old-guard ghost, foretelling that partyâs impending doom.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In an appearance before the Republican Jewish Coalition, he broke from his planned speech to offer an impromptu warning to the conservative lobbying group. After watching Ted Cruz dodge a question about appealing to pro-choice voters, <a href="//www.c-span.org/video/?c4569687/lindsey-graham-abortion">Graham spoke</a> not for his own legitimacy, but for his partyâs.</p>
<div class="w480">
<div class="w480 youtube-video-container">
<div class="youtube-video" data-youtube-id="MWQXM8MB2fs" data-start="">
<div class="thumb"><img src="https://img.youtube.com/vi/MWQXM8MB2fs/0.jpg" />
<div class="playButton">
<div class="arrow"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="caption">Senator Lindsey Graham at the Republican Jewish Coalition</span></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Decrying the partyâs increasingly extreme position on abortion rights, Graham said the G.O.P.âs future âwill be about the nominee of the Republican Party, telling a woman whoâs been raped: âYou gotta carry the child of the rapist.â Good luck with that.â He warned that Republicans would lose not only young women âin droves,â but also most of the rest of America if the party continued its hard-line approach.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He wasnât wrong. An <a href="//ap-gfkpoll.com/featured/ap-gfk-poll-support-for-legal-abortion-at-highest-level-in-2-years">Associated Press-GfK poll</a> found that at the end of 2015, national support for legal abortion rights was at its highest level in the past two years. Support for legal abortion in most or all cases has grown from 51 percent in January 2015 to 58 percent this month. Among Republicans, support for legal abortion rose from 35 to 40 percent in 2015. The G.O.P. is still deeply divided, the poll found: 7 in 10 conservative Republicans oppose abortion rights in most or all cases, yet 6 in 10 moderate and liberal Republicans support the right to choose.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.gallup.com/poll/1576/abortion.aspx">Gallup polls reveal</a> that Americans identifying as pro-choice outnumber those identifying as pro-life. More than half of Americans agree that women should have the legal right to choose under some circumstances, compared to only 19 percent who think abortion should be illegal in all circumstances.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The <a href="//www.lifewayresearch.com/2015/11/23/women-distrust-church-on-abortion/">Christian research group LifeWay Research</a> recently found that 7 in 10 abortion recipients identify as Christian, and 43 percent of women who had abortions attended church during the time they decided abortion was the right choice for their unwanted pregnancy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet the presidential candidates left standing proved this year that they are not interested in reaching these potential supporters. Marco Rubio <a href="//www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/aug/09/marco-rubio-record-opponent-of-abortion">said</a> contemporary Americans would be remembered as âbarbariansâ who murdered âmillions of babies,â and Ben Carson compared women seeking abortions <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2015/10/25/ben-carson-likens-abortion-to-slavery-wants-to-see-roe-v-wade-overturned/">to slaveholders</a>.Â Carly Fiorinaâs rhetoric of âbutchering babies for body partsâ was echoed by the suspect in the Planned Parenthood shooting that left three dead.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In Congress, too, Republicans who support abortion rights are few and far between. Representative Richard Hanna was one of the three Republicans in the House who voted against defunding Planned Parenthood in September. He has been vocal about the mission of Planned Parenthood â providing education and contraception, which means fewer unintended pregnancies and fewer abortions, in addition to inexpensive womenâs health care. On a <a href="https://soundcloud.com/bill-keeler/12-14-15-seg-9">radio show this month</a>, Mr. Hanna asked the questions all modern Republicans should ask themselves: âDo you really want women not to have access to health care?â and, âDo you believe in a womanâs right to have domain over her body, or the governmentâs?â He is likely to face a challenger in his primary in 2016, perhaps one who will toe the party line better.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The PAC <a href="//www.gopchoice.org/">Republican Majority for Choice</a> identifies Mr. Hanna as one of the few Republicans defending womenâs basic rights against government overreach. Others include Senator <a href="//talkingpointsmemo.com/dc/susan-collins-would-strike-planned-parenthood-provision-from-reconciliation-bill">Susan Collins</a> of Maine, who is outspoken on the importance of Planned Parenthood health care services; Senator <a href="//www.alaskapublic.org/2015/09/24/this-time-murkowski-votes-with-democrats-on-planned-parenthood/">Lisa Murkowski</a> of Alaska who has supported Title X and federal family planning programs; Senator Mark Kirk of Illinois; and Representatives Charles Dent of Pennsylvania and Rodney Frelinghuysen of New Jersey. But as the party line has become a hard line, many pro-choice conservative politicians have found themselves at odds with their fellow Republicans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A <a href="//www.vox.com/2015/12/18/10587126/un-womens-rights-embarrassment">U.N. working group</a>Â studied the condition of American womenâs liberties in 2015. The group <a href="//www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=16872&amp;amp;LangID=E">noted</a> that American âwomen fall behind international standards as regards their public and political representation, their economic and social rights and their health and safety protections.â Citing the ever-present threats and harassment against workers and patients at womenâs health clinics and the erosion of comprehensive sex education, the group concluded that âU.S. women do not take their rightful place as citizens of the worldâs leading economy,â due to repeated infringements on their basic human rights.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Women who are allowed to exercise their reproductive liberties are able to pursue their own economic independence and have children they can afford at a time that is right for them. Doesnât that sound like the Republican Partyâs <a href="https://www.gop.com/our-gop/">stated aim</a>: âa freer and stronger America where everyone has the opportunity to achieve the American dreamâ?</p>
	</div>
